Resolves and stages everything a "billed" (subscription-auth) cage launch needs on the host: locates the real `claude` binary, finds the host's OAuth credential file, and synthesizes a minimal `~/.claude.json` written into the run directory before container start. This is the piece that lets an offline cage authenticate as the operator's Claude Code subscription without ever seeing the rest of `~/.claude` or prompting for login.

The core invariant is blinding: only `~/.claude/.credentials.json` is bound into the cage (read-only), and the synthesized config carries *only* the host's `oauthAccount` object plus onboarding/trust pre-completion fields — no project history, no other credentials. API calls still leave the cage exclusively through the host proxy relay at `CAGE_BASE_URL = "http://127.0.0.1:8080"` (set as `ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL` by the caller), which passes the `Authorization` header through untouched; this file doesn't set up that relay, just points claude at it implicitly via the constant it exports.

`resolve_claude_runtime(rundir: &Path, target_root: &Path) -> Result<ClaudeRuntime, CageError>` is the sole entry point, returning a `ClaudeRuntime { claude_binary, credentials, claude_config_json }` — three host paths the caller binds/mounts into the cage. It errors via `CageError::Protocol` if `claude` isn't on `PATH`, `HOME` is unset, or `~/.claude/.credentials.json`/`~/.claude.json` are missing — all recoverable-but-fatal setup issues, never a panic.

Non-obvious behavior worth knowing: `which_claude_realpath` shells out to `readlink -f "$(command -v claude)"` because Claude Code installs `bin/claude` as a symlink to a versioned ELF under `share/` — resolving the symlink is required for correct binding. `build_synth_config` keys the `projects` map by `target_root`'s exact string form (the workspace's real host path per ADR-046, no fixed alias) because that's the same key claude's own trust map checks — any mismatch between this path and where the cage actually mounts the project reopens the trust dialog and breaks headless operation. `random_anonymous_id` reads raw bytes from `/dev/urandom` directly (not `rand`) since only per-run freshness for telemetry is needed, not cryptographic randomness; failure to open the file silently falls back to an all-zero buffer rather than erroring.

Depends on `serde_json` for building/parsing config values; no other unusual crates.